  "upgrade_suggestion": "1975 US Capitol reissue is a workable mid-period pressing; the audiophile alternative is the original 1971 UK Harvest (SHVL 795) — meaningfully better sound but expensive. The 2016 James Guthrie remaster is the cleanest digital source.",
  "commentary": "Released October/November 1971, *Meddle* is the album where Pink Floyd figured out their next decade. Coming off *Ummagumma*'s solo-segment experiments and *Atom Heart Mother*'s orchestral-suite ambitions, the band needed to consolidate — and *Meddle* is the document of that consolidation.\n\nThe breakthrough is *Echoes*, the 23-minute side-2 piece that became the prototype for everything from *Dark Side of the Moon* through *Wish You Were Here*. The band built it from a year of recorded fragments labeled \"Nothing, Pts. 1-24\" — keyboard sketches, guitar phrases, sound effects — that they assembled at Abbey Road, AIR Studios, and Morgan Sound through early 1971. Richard Wright's submarine-ping piano (the famous opening note, processed through a Leslie cabinet) was an accident: he hit a single note while testing the equipment and the band kept it. *Echoes* is the first time Floyd's signature dynamic-and-spatial language fully cohered.\n\nSide 1 is openly transitional. *One of These Days* (Roger Waters' twin-bass instrumental with Nick Mason's vocoder-spoken \"I am about to cut you into little pieces\") points forward; *San Tropez* and *Fearless* are pleasant but conventional rock songs the band was unsure about; *Seamus* features David Gilmour's actual dog Seamus howling along to a 12-bar blues — recorded for real, the dog was at the studio with Steve Marriott (who was minding him for a tour), and Gilmour played him an open tuning until he started singing. The band has since called *Seamus* a mistake; Roger Waters said in 1972 that they thought it was funny at the time.\n\n**About this US Capitol pressing:** Capitol issued *Meddle* as `SMAS-832` from late 1971 onward. Multiple plants pressed it across the early-to-mid 1970s — your \"early/mid-1970s\" frame matches a 1974 repress or a 1975 reissue depending on the deadwax stamps. The captured ID (r7651494) is the 1975 reissue with documented etched runouts (`Smas-1-832 H-35 Jay ─◁` / `SMAS-2-832 G44#2 ─◁`); the `─◁` triangle is Capitol's mastering mark and the letter-number combos identify the cutting engineer and cut number.\n\n*Deadwax TBD — `H-35 Jay` would confirm r7651494 (1975 Reissue); absence of those etched marks would point to the 1974 Repress (r27609675) or another variant. Re-point if needed once the runouts are read.*\n\n### Gemini Notes\n\nReleased in 1971, *Meddle* is the transitional masterpiece where Pink Floyd found their signature sound, anchored by the 23-minute epic \"Echoes.\" It moves away from their psychedelic origins toward the structured, progressive brilliance that would define their 70s output.\n\n**About this pressing:**",
